04437nam a22005535i 9781438468532DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9781438468532  a(DE-B1597)682567  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43019qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aDeAngelis, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRx Hollywood :bCinema and Therapy in the 1960s /cMichael DeAngelis. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (236 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 12  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series, Horizons of Cinema00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAnalyst/Patient Relationships -- tTherapy and the Sexual Block -- tMarriage Therapies and Women's Liberation -- tPsychedelic Therapies -- tTherapy and Confession -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRx Hollywood investigates how therapy surfaced in the themes, representations, and narrative strategies of a changing film industry. In the 1960s and early 1970s, American cinema was struggling to address adult audiences who were increasingly demanding films that confronted contemporary issues. Focusing upon five fields of therapeutic inquiry—therapist/patient dynamics, female "frigidity" and male impotence, marital discord, hallucinogenic drug use, and the dynamics of confession—Michael DeAngelis argues that the films of this period reveal an emergent, common tendency of therapy to work toward the formation of a stronger sense of interpersonal, community/social, and political engagement, counteracting alienation and social division in the spirit of connection and community.Prior to the 1960s, therapy had been considered an introspective process, one that emphasized contemplation and insight and prompted the patient to investigate memories and past traumas. In the 1960s, however, therapy would move toward more humanistic, client-centered, community, group, and encounter models that deemphasized the "there and then" of past feelings and experiences and embraced the "here and now" of the present. These kinds of therapy promised to heal the self through a process of reaching out, helping individuals to connect with communities, support networks, and other like-minded individuals who shared a needed sense of belonging.Drawing on a wide range of films, including Marnie, The Boston Strangler, The Chapman Report, Carnal Knowledge, Divorce American Style, Diary of a Mad Housewife, Guess Who's Coming to Dinner, and Five Easy Pieces, DeAngelis shows how American culture framed therapeutic issues as problems of human communication, developing treatment strategies that addressed individual psychological problems as social problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychiatry in motion pictures. 0aPsychoanalysis and motion pictures. 0aPsychoanalysis in motion pictures. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aPsychology : Psychiatry. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438468532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438468532/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles